<doc id="1063395" wikidata="Q6326670" url="?curid=1063395" title="KCDSA">
<text>KCDSA (Korean Certificate-based Digital Signature Algorithm) is a digital signature algorithm created by a team led by the Korea Internet &amp; Security Agency (KISA). It is an ElGamal variant, similar to the Digital Signature Algorithm and GOST R 34.10-94. The standard algorithm is implemented over formula_1, but an elliptic curve variant (EC-KCDSA) is also specified.

KCDSA requires a collision-resistant cryptographic hash function that can produce a variable-sized output (from 128 to 256 bits, in 32-bit increments). HAS-160, another Korean standard, is the suggested choice.

==Domain parameters==
* formula_2: a large prime such that formula_3 for formula_4.
* formula_5: a prime factor of formula_6 such that formula_7 for formula_8.
* formula_9: a base element of order formula_5 in formula_11.

The revised version of the spec additional requires either that formula_12 be prime or that all of its prime factors are greater than formula_5.

==User parameters==
* formula_14: signer&#x27;s private signature key such that formula_15.
* formula_16: signer&#x27;s public verification key computed by formula_17 where formula_18.
* formula_19: a hash-value of &quot;Cert Data&quot;, i.e., formula_20.

The 1998 spec is unclear about the exact format of the &quot;Cert Data&quot;. In the revised spec, z is defined as being the bottom B bits of the public key y, where B is the block size of the hash function in bits (typically 512 or 1024). The effect is that the first input block corresponds to y mod 2^B.

* formula_19: the lower B bits of y.

==Hash Function==
* formula_22: a collision resistant hash function with |q|-bit digests.

==Signing==

To sign a message formula_23:

* Signer randomly picks an integer formula_24 and computes formula_25
* Then computes the first part: formula_26
* Then computes the second part: formula_27
* If formula_28, the process must be repeated from the start.
* The signature is formula_29

The specification is vague about how the integer formula_30 be reinterpreted as a byte string input to hash function. In the example in section C.1 the interpretation is consistent with formula_31 using the definition of I2OSP from PKCS#1/RFC3447.

==Verifying==

To verify a signature formula_29 on a message formula_23:

* Verifier checks that formula_34 and formula_35 and rejects the signature as invalid if not.
* Verifier computes formula_36
* Verifier checks if formula_37. If so then the signature is valid; otherwise it is not valid.

==EC-KCDSA==

EC-KCDSA is essentially the same algorithm using Elliptic-curve cryptography instead of discrete log cryptography.

The domain parameters are:
* An elliptic curve formula_38 over a finite field. 
* A point formula_39 in formula_38 generating a cyclic subgroup of prime order formula_5. (formula_5 is often denoted formula_43 in other treatments of elliptic-curve cryptography.)

The user parameters and algorithms are essentially the same as for discrete log KCDSA except that modular exponentiation is replaced by point multiplication. The specific differences are:
* The public key is formula_44
* In signature generation, formula_45 where formula_46
* In signature verification, the verifier tests whether formula_47

